					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/pedantique" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3118444); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3118444&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183388" alt="Pedantique" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3118444)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/pedantique" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3118444); return false;" >Pedantique</a></span> <span class="odate time_1572091091 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Oct 2019 11:58</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4407321">
									

<p>I enjoyed this enough to upvote on atmosphere and mechanics, but the creepiness of it (which I assume was the main thrust?) felt extremely subdued, largely because the weird thing is entirely explainable. It's noted early in the article that there was lots of fanbrewing to fill gaps in the product, so something weird showing up that wasn't in the base game feels expected. The fact that everything operates according to arcane probability tables also seems to explain how the minotaur could always arrive to deflect players approaching victory. I'm not sure if you <em>want</em> the punch to be stronger or not, but it seems like it definitely could be.</p>

							</div>

								
